{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14232"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14232"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.42,0.22,0.2,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6919"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"4612"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with severe acute kidney injury secondary to septic shock. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include amlodipine and metformin. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on 2 L/min oxygen, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has pitting oedema up to his knees and decreased urine output of 100 mL total over the past 24 hours. Laboratory investigations reveal a serum potassium of 5.3 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), bicarbonate of 12 mmol/L (22-28), and urea of 35 mmol/L (2.5-6.7). An ECG shows sinus tachycardia without other changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer sodium bicarbonate","Start renal replacement therapy","Increase intravenous fluid administration","Administer insulin-dextrose infusion","Administer intravenous furosemide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe acute kidney injury (AKI) complicated by mild hyperkalaemia, severe metabolic acidosis, and volume overload. The most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Estart renal replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E to comprehensively address these complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal replacement therapy encompasses various modalities including haemodialysis, haemofiltration, and peritoneal dialysis. In the acute intensive care setting, continuous renal replacement therapy (CRRT) would be the most appropriate method of choice. These therapies can effectively correct electrolyte imbalances, metabolic acidosis, and fluid overload by removing waste products and excess fluid from the blood through a semipermeable membrane. RRT can manage the mild hyperkalaemia, correct the severe acidosis, and remove excess fluid, addressing all of this patient\u0027s critical issues simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreasing \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid administration\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen the volume overload and is contraindicated in this context, given the patient\u0027s oedema and oliguria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministering \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered to manage volume overload, but it is unlikely to be effective given the severity of the AKI and the patient\u0027s minimal urine output. Moreover, it does not address the acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to correct metabolic acidosis, it does not address the hyperkalaemia or volume overload and is not sufficient as a standalone treatment in this scenario. It may also worsen fluid overload.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einsulin-dextrose infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is used as an emergency temporising measure for severe hyperkalaemia with ECG changes. Since this patient has only mild hyperkalaemia (5.3 mmol/L) without ECG changes, there is no hyperkalaemic emergency requiring immediate temporising measures. The mild hyperkalaemia should be addressed alongside the other complications through renal replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the severity of this patient\u0027s condition with multiple complications of AKI, including severe metabolic acidosis, volume overload, and hyperkalaemia, renal replacement therapy is the most appropriate next step as it comprehensively addresses all of the patient\u0027s critical issues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal replacement therapy is indicated in severe acute kidney injury with complications such as hyperkalaemia, severe metabolic acidosis, volume overload unresponsive to diuretics, and uraemic complications.","Renal replacement therapy encompasses various modalities including haemodialysis and haemofiltration, which can effectively manage electrolyte imbalances, acidosis, uremia, and fluid overload in acute kidney injury."],"references":["Lisa Gemmell, Robert Docking, Euan Black, Renal replacement therapy in critical care, BJA Education, Volume 17, Issue 3, March 2017, Pages 88\u201393, https://doi.org/10.1093/bjaed/mkw070"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T18:03:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T18:03:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6919"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id